In article &lt;ENAG.90Aug6201933@svarte.ifi.uio.no&gt;, I wrote:
&gt;&gt; Can you explain what makes you think it is _not_ legal?

In article &lt;TOWFIQ.90Aug7105422@interlan.Interlan.COM&gt;, Mark Towfigh writes:
&gt; "UK" is not a valid top-level domain -- the correct one is "GB".

"UK" is not a valid two-letter country abbreviation according to ISO
3166, where the correct one is "GB".

Valid domain names are decided by the NIC and the HOSTMASTER (correct
me if wrong).  The NIC has decided that "UK" is a valid top-level
domain.  The NIC has also decided that we should follow ISO 3166
two-letter country abbreviations for national top-level domain names.
So what?  I believe the adoption of "UK" for that island predates the
adoption of ISO 3166 as the standard for national top-level domain
labels.  Can anyone confirm this?

I bet if you bugged the NIC enough, with sufficiently good arguments,
you'd get your own three-letter top-level domain name, as well.  I
think that is what happened with the INT domain.

In principle, any random, syntactically legal (that's about the only
"legal" you can find) string of characters can be used as a top-level
domain name.  The NIC is the final arbiter, though.

Let's put this part of the UK issue to rest, and concentrate on what
they _do_ wrong now, instead of what someone, sometime _did_ do wrong.

[Erik Naggum]

